(20, 'Apple', 'Apples are nutritious and provide several health benefits:', 'here are thousands of apple varieties, with some of the most popular including:\n\nFuji: Sweet and juicy, great for eating raw.\nGranny Smith: Tart and crisp, ideal for baking.\nGala: Mildly sweet and fragrant, perfect for snacking.\nHoneycrisp: Known for its balance of sweetness and tartness, with an excellent crunch.\nNutritional Benefits\nApples are nutritious and provide several health benefits:\n\nLow in Calories: A medium apple has about 95 calories.\nFiber: Good source of dietary fiber, which aids digestion.\nVitamins: Rich in vitamin C and various antioxidants.\nHeart Health: May help reduce the risk of heart disease due to their high fiber and antioxidant content.\nGrowing Conditions\nClimate: Apples thrive in temperate climates.\nSoil: Well-drained, loamy soil is ideal.\nPollination: Most apple varieties require cross-pollination for optimal fruit production.\nCulinary Uses\nRaw: Eaten fresh, sliced, or in salads.\nBaking: Commonly used in pies, crisps, and cakes.\nSauces and Ciders: Made into applesauce or fermented into hard cider.\nStorage\nStore apples in a cool, dry place', 'top-review', 'fruits', 'istockphoto-1214421019-612x612.jpg', 3000, '5'),
(22, 'Cashew', 'Cashew nuts grow attached to the cashew apple, which is also edible and often used to make juices and jams.', '<h3>Botanical Information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Scientific Name</strong>: Anacardium occidentale</li>\r\n<li><strong>Family</strong>: Anacardiaceae</li>\r\n<li><strong>Origin</strong>: Native to Brazil, cashews are now cultivated in tropical regions around the world, including India, Vietnam, and Nigeria.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Nutritional Benefits</h3>\r\n<p>Cashews are nutritious and provide several health benefits:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Healthy Fats</strong>: High in monounsaturated fats, which are beneficial for heart health.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Protein</strong>: A good source of plant-based protein.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Vitamins and Minerals</strong>: Rich in magnesium, phosphorus, copper, and zinc.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Antioxidants</strong>: Contains compounds like carotenoids and phenolic compounds that can help reduce inflammation.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Culinary Uses</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Raw</strong>: Eaten as a snack or added to salads.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Roasted</strong>: Commonly roasted and salted for a savory snack.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Dairy Alternatives</strong>: Used to make cashew milk, cream, and cheese in vegan cooking.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Cooking</strong>: Added to stir-fries, curries, and desserts for texture and flavor.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Growing Conditions</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Climate</strong>: Requires a tropical climate with well-defined wet and dry seasons.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Soil</strong>: Prefers well-drained sandy soils.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Harvesting</strong>: The cashew a', 'top-rated', 'dry-fruits', '360_F_278420937_amMUMd0A6H4CjPqzoCMYWHjmGblpXJAx.jpg', 10000, '5'),
(23, 'Vegetable', 'Vegetables can be categorized into several groups:', '<p>Vegetables can be categorized into several groups:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>Leafy Greens</strong>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Examples: Spinach, kale, lettuce, Swiss chard.</li>\r\n<li>Benefits: High in vitamins A, C, K, and minerals like iron and calcium.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>Cruciferous</strong>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Examples: Broccoli, cauliflower, Brussels sprouts, cabbage.</li>\r\n<li>Benefits: Rich in fiber, vitamins C and K, and compounds that may have cancer-fighting properties.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>Root Vegetables</strong>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Examples: Carrots, beets, turnips, radishes.</li>\r\n<li>Benefits: Generally high in fiber and various vitamins, especially beta-carotene.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>Alliums</strong>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Examples: Onions, garlic, leeks, shallots.</li>\r\n<li>Benefits: Contain compounds that may boost immune function and have anti-inflammatory properties.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>Nightshades</strong>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Examples: Tomatoes, potatoes, eggplants, bell peppers.</li>\r\n<li>Benefits: High in vitamins and antioxidants, particularly lycopene in tomatoes.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>Legumes</strong>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Examples: Peas, beans, lentils.</li>\r\n<li>Benefits: High in protein, fiber, and essential nutrients like iron and folate.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>', 'top-review', 'vegetable', 'images.jfif', 100, '3'),
(24, 'Almond', 'Almonds are a popular and nutritious tree nut known for their crunchy texture and rich flavor. Hereâ€™s a detailed overview:', '<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Healthy Fats</strong>: High in monounsaturated fats, which are heart-healthy.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Protein</strong>: A good source of plant-based protein, providing about 6 grams per ounce.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Vitamins and Minerals</strong>: Rich in vitamin E, magnesium, calcium, and potassium.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Antioxidants</strong>: Contains antioxidants like flavonoids, which help combat oxidative stress.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Culinary Uses</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Raw or Roasted</strong>: Eaten as a snack, either raw or roasted and salted.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Almond Milk</strong>: Used as a dairy alternative in beverages and recipes.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><strong>Climate</strong>: Almond trees thrive in Mediterranean climates with warm, dry summers and mild, wet winters.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Pollination</strong>: Most almond varieties require cross-pollination from other almond trees to produce nuts.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Storage</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Store almonds in an airtight container in a cool, dry place. They can also be refrigerated or frozen for longer shelf life.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>', 'top-selling', 'dry-fruits', 'ho07ndkr-500x500.webp', 4000, '5'),
(26, 'Raisins', 'Raisins are dried grapes that are sweet and chewy, making them a popular snack and ingredient in various dishes. Hereâ€™s a detailed overview:', '<p>Raisins can be categorized based on the type of grape used and their drying methods:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Golden Raisins</strong>: Made from green grapes and dried using sulfur dioxide, resulting in a lighter color and sweeter flavor.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Black Raisins</strong>: Darker in color, usually made from black or red grapes, and typically have a richer flavor.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Sultanas</strong>: Made from a specific type of grape, they are usually plump and juicy with a sweet taste.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Nutritional Benefits</h3>\r\n<p>Raisins are packed with nutrients:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Natural Sugars</strong>: High in natural sugars, providing a quick energy boost.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Fiber</strong>: A good source of dietary fiber, aiding in digestion.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Vitamins and Minerals</strong>: Rich in iron, potassium, and antioxidants like polyphenols, which can promote heart health.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Low in Fat</strong>: Raisins contain minimal fat, making them a healthy snack option.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Culinary Uses</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Snacking</strong>: Eaten alone or mixed with nuts for a trail mix.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Baking</strong>: Commonly added to cookies, bread, and cakes.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Cooking</strong>: Used in savory dishes like rice pilafs and tagines for added sweetness.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Salads</strong>: Tossed into salads for a sweet contrast to savory ingredients.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Storage</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Store raisins in an airtight con', 'top-review', 'dry-fruits', 'DF_06-02_2048x.webp', 500, '4'),
