(35, 'Litchi', ' often described as having a floral flavor. Litchis are typically in season from late spring to summer and ', 'ychee (or litchi) is a tropical fruit known for its sweet, floral flavor and unique texture. Hereâ€™s a detailed overview:\r\n\r\nBotanical Information\r\nScientific Name: Litchi chinensis\r\nFamily: Sapindaceae\r\nOrigin: Native to southern China, lychee is also grown in other tropical and subtropical regions, including India, Thailand, and Vietnam.\r\nNutritional Benefits\r\nLychee is not only delicious but also nutritious:\r\n\r\nLow in Calories: Approximately 66 calories per 100 grams.\r\nVitamins and Minerals: Rich in vitamin C, vitamin B6, copper, and potassium.\r\nAntioxidants: Contains polyphenols, which may have anti-inflammatory and anti-cancer properties.\r\nCulinary Uses\r\nFresh Consumption: Eaten raw as a refreshing snack.\r\nDesserts: Used in fruit salads, sorbets, and puddings.\r\nSavory Dishes: Occasionally added to stir-fries or salads for a sweet contrast.\r\nBeverages: Made into juices, smoothies, or cocktails.\r\nGrowing Conditions\r\nClimate: Thrives in warm, humid climates with plenty of rainfall.\r\nSoil: Prefers well-drained, sandy loam soil.\r\nHarvesting: Lychee fruits are usually harvested when they turn bright red or pink, indicating ripeness.', 'top-selling', 'fruits', '360_F_211908888_nogeeJ77XpXH7MbSgO6DNczsZKrdbaXF.jpg', 500, '5'),
